        <body>
            <div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1975-08-27T23:59:59-05:00"
                frus:doc-dateTime-min="1975-08-27T00:00:00-05:00" n="270"
                subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d270">
                <head>270. Memorandum of Conversation, Seoul, August 27, 1975.<note n="1"
                        type="source" xml:id="d270fn1">Source: <persName corresp="#p_ford-gerald-r"
                            >Ford</persName> Library, National Security Adviser, Presidential
                        Country Files for East Asia and the Pacific, Box 9, Korea (11). Secret;
                        Sensitive; <gloss target="#t_nodis">Nodis</gloss>. The conversation took
                        place in President <persName corresp="#p_park-chung-hee">Park</persName>’s
                        Office. The discussion occurred before and during lunch. Howard Graves,
                        Military Assistant in the Office of the Secretary of Defense, sent this
                            <gloss target="#t_memcon">memcon</gloss> to <persName
                            corresp="#p_scowcroft-brent">Scowcroft</persName> on September 9.</note>
                    <note n="2" type="summary" xml:id="d270fn2">
                        <persName corresp="#p_park-chung-hee">Park</persName> and <persName
                            corresp="#p_schlesinger-james-r">Schlesinger</persName> discussed Japan,
                        human rights, and anti-submarine warfare.</note>
                </head>
                <opener>
                    <dateline>
                        <placeName>Seoul</placeName>, <date
                            ana="#date_undated-inferred-from-document-head" calendar="gregorian"
                            type="conversation-or-meeting-date" when="1975-08-27">August 27,
                            1975</date>
                    </dateline>
                </opener>
                <p>MEMORANDUM OF CONVERSATION</p>
                <list type="participants">
                    <head>PARTICIPANTS</head>
                    <item>President <persName corresp="#p_park-chung-hee">Park Chung Hee</persName>
                    </item>
                    <item>Minister of Defense <persName corresp="#p_suh-jyong-chul">Suh
                            Jyong-chul</persName>
                    </item>
                    <item>
                        <gloss target="#t_rok">ROK</gloss> Chairman of <gloss target="#t_jcs"
                            >JCS</gloss> Ro Jae -hyun</item>
                    <item>Secretary General, Kim Chong-yom</item>
                    <item>Senior Protocol Secretary, Choi Kwan-soo</item>
                    <item>Secretary of Defense <persName corresp="#p_schlesinger-james-r">James R.
                            Schlesinger</persName>
                    </item>
                    <item>Ambassador <persName corresp="#p_sneider-richard-l">Richard L.
                            Sneider</persName>
                    </item>
                    <item>General Richard G. Stilwell</item>
                    <item>Chairman, <gloss target="#t_jcs">JCS</gloss>, General <persName
                            corresp="#p_brown-george-s">George S. Brown</persName>
                    </item>
                    <item>
                        <gloss target="#t_cincpac">CINCPAC</gloss>, Admiral Noel A.M. Gaylen</item>
                    <item>Military Assistant to Secretary of Defense, Maj Gen John A. Wickham</item>
                </list>
                <p>TIME &amp; PLACE: President <persName corresp="#p_park-chung-hee"
                    >Park</persName>’s Office, August 27, 1975</p>
                <p>During the pre-lunch and luncheon conversation, three areas of particular
                    interest were covered.</p>
                <list>
                    <label>1.</label>
                    <item>
                        <p>JAPAN</p>
                        <p>President <persName corresp="#p_park-chung-hee">Park</persName> discussed
                            his concerns about the Japanese attitude toward Korea, particularly his
                            fears about the leftward drift in the Japanese political scene when the
                            younger generation takes over and the diminution of Japanese economic
                            assistance to Korea. During the discussion, Secretary <persName
                                corresp="#p_schlesinger-james-r">Schlesinger</persName> said that he
                            proposed to discuss with Prime Minister <persName
                                corresp="#p_miki-takeo">Miki</persName> the need for greater
                            Japanese economic assistance to Korea.</p>
                    </item>
                    <label>2.</label>
                    <item>
                        <p>HUMAN RIGHTS</p>
                        <p>In the course of discussing recent Congressional visits to Korea,
                            Secretary <persName corresp="#p_schlesinger-james-r"
                                >Schlesinger</persName> noted that President <persName
                                corresp="#p_park-chung-hee">Park</persName>, as a result of these
                            visits, must be aware of Congressional attitudes on human rights and the
                            problems it has caused the Administration.</p>
                    </item>
                    <label>3.</label>
                    <item>
                        <p>ASW</p>
                        <p>President <persName corresp="#p_park-chung-hee">Park</persName> described
                            his rationale for acquisition of submarines. He said that, in order to
                            deal with the North Korean submarine threat both during a period of
                            conflict and to present infiltration and subversive efforts, he wished
                            to acquire a comparable capability. He felt that, if the <gloss
                                target="#t_rok">ROK</gloss> had similar capability, North Korea
                            would not utilize its submarines. Secretary <persName
                                corresp="#p_schlesinger-james-r">Schlesinger</persName> suggested
                            that there are probably more cost-effective ways for dealing with the
                            North Korean submarine threat than purchasing or <pb facs="d270-2" n="2"
                                xml:id="d270-2"/> building submarines in the South. He mentioned use
                            of P–3’s and sensors for the detection and if necessary destruction of
                            the submarines. He also stressed the vulnerability of the North Korean
                            ports to mining and other techniques to close these ports. It was agreed
                            that the U.S. would provide experts to review the options available to
                            deal with the North Korean submarine threat. In addition, the Secretary
                            asked General <persName corresp="#p_brown-george-s">Brown</persName> and
                            Admiral Gayler to look into P–3 operations in the Korean area.</p>
                    </item>
                </list>
            </div>
